# Laws of UX — apps and dashboards only

## Scope

**Apply** when creating or editing **internal applications and dashboards**: multi-step forms, wizards, agent UIs, workplan builders, intake flows, admin panels, and their HTML/CSS/JS.

**Do not apply** to:

- Client-facing **slide decks** (HTML slides, PPTX, `slide_workspace_v0`, compile/screenshot slide skills)
- **Slide preview rails** (e.g. `.page` / horizontal slide chrome inside deck exports)
- LoP **chapter prose**, memos, or outline Markdown unless the user is explicitly building app UI

For all deck and client-slide work, use [`mckinsey-document-standards.mdc`](mckinsey-document-standards.mdc) and slide-authoring skills — not this rule.

## Source of truth

Use principles from **[Laws of UX](https://lawsofux.com/)** (Jon Yablonski). Name laws from that collection; do not invent alternate "UX laws."

For detail and a pre-flight checklist, read **[`.cursor/skills/laws-of-ux/SKILL.md`](../skills/laws-of-ux/SKILL.md)** before proposing UI changes.

## Workflow

1. Identify the user task (navigation, form, feedback, density, onboarding).
2. Map 2-4 relevant laws from [lawsofux.com](https://lawsofux.com/) to concrete UI choices.
3. Implement; briefly state which laws informed the change (one sentence each is enough).

Use WebFetch on a specific law page when you need the full definition.

## Priority

On **apps and dashboards**, Laws of UX are **primary** for layout, interaction, feedback, information architecture, and accessibility of flows.

McKinsey slide typography/palette/pyramid rules do **not** govern app chrome unless the user asks to align a screen with firm slide styling.

## Files this rule typically covers

Examples: `intake.html`, `*dashboard*.html`, `lop-agents-ui/`, `lop-builder-dashboard.html`. A path may contain both app UI and embedded slide previews — apply Laws of UX only to the **application** surfaces (forms, steps, side panels, tables), not to slide deck markup inside the same file.
